Note:
==============================================================================
SECURE_MEMORY - Memory wiping and constant-time memory primitives
==============================================================================

Provides cryptographic-grade memory operations:

1. secure_zero(ptr, len) - explicit_bzero equivalent. Writes zero bytes
   into [ptr, ptr+len) using a volatile-fenced loop so the optimizer
   cannot elide the writes the way it can with memset. This is the
   ONLY correct primitive for wiping key material, nonces, and other
   secrets before deallocation.

2. constant_time_compare(a, b, len) - timing-side-channel-safe byte
   comparison. Iterates the full length regardless of mismatches and
   returns 1 if equal, 0 if not equal. Used for MAC tag comparisons
   and any other comparison whose result is itself security-relevant.

3. constant_time_select(condition, a, b) - branchless conditional that
   returns a if condition is 1 and b if condition is 0. Implemented
   without a branch by sign-extending the negation of condition into
   a mask. Used inside constant-time primitives to avoid leaking the
   condition via branch prediction.

4. memory_clobber_barrier(ptr) - inserts an inline assembly "memory"
   clobber so the compiler cannot reorder reads of secret data across
   the barrier. Used in conjunction with secure_zero to guarantee the
   wipe happens before the buffer is freed.

The composition of these four primitives is the foundation that every
constant-time primitive in this crypto library uses to express its
side-channel-safe arithmetic.

References:
- BoringSSL OPENSSL_cleanse: same pattern (volatile pointer loop + asm
  memory clobber).
- libsodium sodium_memzero: same pattern.
- C11 memset_s and POSIX explicit_bzero: same intent but unavailable in
  freestanding Runa, so we re-implement on top of Runa inline asm.
- D. J. Bernstein, "Cache-timing attacks on AES", 2005: rationale for
  constant-time comparison and selection.
:End Note

Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/core/memory_core.runa" as Memory
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/assembly/atomic.runa" as Atomic

Note: ============================================================================
Note: SECTION 1: secure_zero
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "secure_zero" takes ptr as Integer, length as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Overwrites [ptr, ptr+length) with zero bytes in a way the optimizer
    cannot eliminate. A naive memset is legally optimized away by C/Runa
    compilers when the buffer is about to go out of scope or be freed,
    which is the precise case in which we need the wipe to actually
    happen. This implementation calls memory_set_byte through Runa's
    proc-call boundary which the Runa compiler does not currently
    inline across, providing dead-store elimination resistance.

    A final memory_clobber_barrier is issued after the loop so even
    if a future optimizer learns to elide proc-call dead stores, the
    barrier forces the wipe to be observed before any subsequent use
    of the buffer.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Walks each byte index from 0 to length-1, writing 0 via
    memory_set_byte. We deliberately do not batch into qwords to keep
    the implementation maximally simple and resistant to vectorizer
    fusion of the zero stores into a non-temporal hint. After the
    loop, an asm memory barrier finalizes ordering.

    Returns 1 on success, 0 if ptr is null or length is negative.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    Bytewise zeroing is slower than qword zeroing but cryptographic
    wipe is invoked on small key buffers (32-256 bytes typically), so
    the overhead is negligible. Do not use this for general buffer
    zeroing; use memory_zero from memory_core for that.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Hardened against: compiler dead-store-elimination of the zero
    writes (the primary failure mode of naive memset for secret wipe).

    Out of scope: cold-boot DRAM remanence attacks (defeated only by
    hardware-level memory encryption such as Intel TME or AMD SME),
    physical bus probing, swap-file leakage (defeated by mlock; see
    secure_mlock below).

    References:
    - Halderman et al., "Lest We Remember: Cold Boot Attacks on
      Encryption Keys", USENIX Security 2008.
    - BoringSSL crypto/mem.c OPENSSL_cleanse.
    @End Security_Scope

    If ptr is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    If length is less than 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    If length is equal to 0:
        Return 1
    End If

    Let i be 0
    While i is less than length:
        proc memory_set_byte from Memory with ptr, i, 0
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While

    proc memory_barrier_full from Atomic
    Return 1
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: SECTION 2: constant_time_compare
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "constant_time_compare" takes a as Integer, b as Integer, length as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Compares two byte buffers of the given length in time independent
    of the contents. The standard memcmp returns early on first
    mismatch, which leaks the position of the first differing byte to
    a timing-side-channel observer; for MAC tags this means an
    attacker can recover the correct tag byte-by-byte in O(256*len)
    forgery attempts rather than O(2^len). This implementation
    accumulates the bitwise difference of every byte pair into a
    single accumulator and returns the equality of the accumulator
    with zero, after walking the entire buffer.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    1. Initialize diff = 0.
    2. For each i in [0, length): diff |= (a[i] XOR b[i]).
    3. Return 1 if diff == 0, else 0.

    The XOR-OR accumulation has the property that diff is zero if
    and only if every byte pair is equal. Crucially, the loop body
    has no early exit, so the branch profile is identical regardless
    of where (or whether) the buffers differ.

    The final step that converts diff to a boolean is itself
    constant-time: we fold diff to a single bit via (diff | -diff) >> 63
    style arithmetic and subtract from 1.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    O(length) regardless of contents. For typical 16-32 byte tags this
    is a handful of nanoseconds and not on any hot path.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Hardened against: timing side-channels on the position of the
    first differing byte. This is the canonical defense against
    Lucky13-style MAC oracle attacks and against ad-hoc forgery
    oracles in any protocol that uses naive memcmp on a MAC.

    Out of scope: cache-line-aligned access patterns (both buffers
    are read fully so all relevant lines are touched equally),
    branch-prediction on the loop counter (the counter range is the
    public length, not secret-dependent).

    References:
    - Lucky13: Al Fardan and Paterson, "Lucky Thirteen: Breaking
      the TLS and DTLS record protocols", IEEE S&P 2013.
    - Coda Hale, "A Lesson in Timing Attacks", 2009.
    @End Security_Scope

    If length is less than 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    If length is equal to 0:
        Return 1
    End If
    If a is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    If b is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let diff be 0
    Let i be 0
    While i is less than length:
        Let byte_a be proc memory_get_byte from Memory with a, i
        Let byte_b be proc memory_get_byte from Memory with b, i
        Let xor_val be byte_a bitwise_xor byte_b
        Set diff to diff bitwise_or xor_val
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While

    Note: Constant-time fold of diff -> {0,1} without a branch.
    Note: diff is in [0, 255] because each xor_val byte is bit-masked.
    Note: For nonzero diff, (diff bitwise_or (0 minus diff)) has bit 63 set
    Note: in two's complement; for zero diff, the result is zero.
    Note: Shifting right by 63 yields 1 for nonzero, 0 for zero. We
    Note: then return 1 minus that to invert (equal = 1, differ = 0).
    Let neg_diff be 0 minus diff
    Let or_val be diff bitwise_or neg_diff
    Let sign_bit be or_val shifted right by 63
    Let is_nonzero be sign_bit bitwise_and 1
    Return 1 minus is_nonzero
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: SECTION 3: constant_time_select
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "constant_time_select" takes condition as Integer, a as Integer, b as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Returns a when condition is 1 and b when condition is 0, without
    using a branch. A branched implementation leaks the condition
    bit via branch-prediction state and via cache-line access on the
    selected value. This implementation computes the result as
    a XOR ((a XOR b) AND mask) where mask is all-ones if condition
    is 0 and all-zeros if condition is 1, derived branchlessly from
    the condition input.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    1. Build mask = 0 - condition (interpreting condition as a single
       bit). When condition = 1, mask = -1 = all-ones in two's
       complement. When condition = 0, mask = 0.
    2. Return (a AND mask) OR (b AND NOT(mask)).

    The mask construction is purely arithmetic with no branches.
    The selection itself uses bitwise operations whose timing is
    architecture-independent.

    Precondition: condition must be 0 or 1. Callers MUST sanitize
    inputs (e.g., normalize_to_bool below) before passing.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    Single-digit-nanosecond cost. The compiler may further fuse this
    into a CMOV on x86-64, which is also constant-time on the cores
    we target.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Hardened against: branch-prediction leakage of the condition,
    cache-side-channel leakage of which input was selected. Both a
    and b are accessed regardless of condition.

    Out of scope: speculative execution leakage of the unused branch
    (this is a CPU microarchitectural concern; mitigated only via
    LFENCE-style speculation barriers which are not yet plumbed into
    Runa's codegen).
    @End Security_Scope

    Let cond_bit be condition bitwise_and 1
    Let mask be 0 minus cond_bit
    Let not_mask be mask bitwise_xor 0 minus 1
    Let from_a be a bitwise_and mask
    Let from_b be b bitwise_and not_mask
    Return from_a bitwise_or from_b
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: SECTION 4: memory_clobber_barrier
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "memory_clobber_barrier" returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Emits an inline assembly "memory" clobber so the compiler cannot
    reorder loads or stores across this point. Used immediately after
    secure_zero to ensure the wipe is observed before any subsequent
    use of the buffer, and around constant-time arithmetic to prevent
    the optimizer from hoisting branches based on secret data.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Delegates to the platform memory_barrier_full primitive in
    primitives/assembly/atomic.runa which on x86-64 emits mfence,
    on aarch64 emits "dmb sy", and on other architectures the
    appropriate full memory ordering instruction.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    No wall-clock cost beyond preventing reorderings. The compiler
    is unable to merge surrounding memory operations across the
    barrier, which is the desired behavior here.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Hardened against: compiler reordering that would expose secret
    data after a wipe or that would hoist secret-dependent branches.

    Out of scope: CPU memory ordering (we emit appropriate fences on
    architectures that need them, but full sequential-consistency is
    not required for the use case).
    @End Security_Scope

    proc memory_barrier_full from Atomic
    Return 1
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: SECTION 5: normalize_to_bool
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "normalize_to_bool" takes value as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Converts an arbitrary integer to canonical {0, 1} in constant
    time. Used to sanitize inputs to constant_time_select where the
    caller may have a 0/nonzero condition rather than a 0/1 bit.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Returns ((value | -value) >> 63) & 1. For value == 0 the result
    is 0, for any nonzero value the result is 1. The shift exploits
    the sign-bit of two's complement representation: any nonzero
    value combined with its negation has the sign bit set.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    Single-digit-nanosecond cost. No branches.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Constant-time conversion. The output is a function of the input
    value only through arithmetic and bitwise operations.
    @End Security_Scope

    Let neg_val be 0 minus value
    Let or_val be value bitwise_or neg_val
    Let sign_bit be or_val shifted right by 63
    Return sign_bit bitwise_and 1
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: SECTION 6: secure_zero_qwords (fast path for aligned buffers)
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "secure_zero_qwords" takes ptr as Integer, qword_count as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Faster wipe for buffers known to be 8-byte aligned and a multiple
    of 8 bytes in length, such as BigInt limb arrays. Same dead-store
    elimination resistance as secure_zero via the proc-call boundary
    and trailing memory barrier.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Walks i in [0, qword_count) writing 0 via memory_set_qword. After
    the loop, an asm memory barrier is issued.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    8x faster than secure_zero for aligned buffers. Use this for
    BigInt and large key-material buffers.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Same as secure_zero. The wipe is not elided by the optimizer
    because the writes cross a proc-call boundary and are fenced by
    a trailing memory barrier.
    @End Security_Scope

    If ptr is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    If qword_count is less than 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    If qword_count is equal to 0:
        Return 1
    End If

    Let i be 0
    While i is less than qword_count:
        proc memory_set_qword from Memory with ptr, i multiplied by 8, 0
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While

    proc memory_barrier_full from Atomic
    Return 1
End Process
